    <h2 class="wp-block-heading">Overview</h2>
    <p>
        Having experience with WordPress and PHP development, I was intrigued by
        the Laravel framework and eventually took an online course to learn
        about it. I found its developer features very easy to use and
        appreciated all of the built in features, like ORM, authentication, and
        templating. After a couple practice projects, I decided to put my skills
        to the test creating Local Picks, using online resources and
        documentation to fill in any gaps. As a quick learner, I appreciated the
        abundance of online information surrounding Laravel. It was easy to get
        started, and as I ran into new use cases, there was always a solution
        that integrated well.
    </p>
    <p>
        Developing a completely custom web directory using an unfamiliar
        framework was no small undertaking, but I was able to take it chunk by
        chunk and add on features as I came up with ideas. I also got a friend
        involved who’s learning computer science and learned how to collaborate
        effectively using git. Together, we were able to make turn this idea
        into a robust web app with impressive features.
    </p>
    <h2 class="wp-block-heading">Create A Listing Form</h2>
    <p>
        The listing creation form went through several iterations before I
        settled on the final design. It was imperative that the form was simple
        to use, yet have robust features available for farmers to use to
        customize their listing and help it stand out. I broke it up into
        several sections, including validation every step of the way and
        features that make it quick and easy to fill out. For example, the form
        identifies any products from the farm name and description and suggests
        they be added in the “products” section later on.
    </p>
    <h2 class="wp-block-heading">Search Page</h2>
    <p>
        Next, it is very important that users are able to easily find and filter
        through farms listed on our platform. This was a significant backend
        task that Laravel’s ORM made very simple. I was able to incorporate
        filters, search within a radius of a provided city or zip code, and
        search suggestions that auto-populate based on farm names, products, and
        tags in our database.
    </p>
</Project>
